observations.recommendation:
Require the GSO-Designate and the Municipal Assessor to exert effort in the retrieval of land titles and other necessary documents as basis to establish ownership and determine proper valuation;

Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the Municipal Government of Esperanza to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third-party claims; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to verify the recorded and unrecorded Land items to properly account them using the cost or fair value and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in accordance with IPSAS 17 or any other applicable accounting standards.

Direct officers and employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers or refund the amount, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

Submit to COA the liquidation reports on the cash advances of the Municipal Treasurer in CY 2023 that were already submitted to her after the preparation of the financial statements, for the Audit Team to verify the balances of each affected cash advances;

Closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period;

Fast track the recovery of the transmittal letters submitted to ICFAU for the liquidation of cash advances for confidential and intelligence expenses which amounted to ₱415,800.00, submit the same to COA and prepare necessary adjusting entries on the relevant cash advances; and

Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the cash advances of the deceased and separated accountable officers and conduct verification, analysis and validation of these cash advances to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Ensure that every cash advances for payroll have schedules of the actual salary of the Agency’s officials and employees payable to them during distributions. This is to avoid instances where the amount of liquidation is more than the amount of the actual cash advance;

Ensure that the advances for operating expenses have sufficient and relevant documents to establish the basis in granting the cash advances as well as supporting documents in determining the reasonableness of the same;

Ensure that every liquidation of his cash advances have references, such as putting the check numbers/voucher numbers of the cash advance to which they relate. This will help the monitoring of the balances of every cash advance; and

Stop the practice of having cash advances without legally authorized specific purpose and for payments of goods and services. Procurement of goods and services must be made through regular modes of procurement provided in RA No. 9184, and payment must be made directly to suppliers and not through cash advances.

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference in the balance of the Cash-Local Treasury between their Offices submit their working papers/reconciliation documents to the Office of the Auditor, and prepare necessary correcting entries in the Agency’s books;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer, by issuing a demand letter, to deposit any unremitted collections in CY 2022 and submit the deposit slips to the Office of the Auditor;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to deposit all future collections intact with the AGDB and not to retain portion of them pursuant to Section 32 of MNGAS for LGUs and Section 28 of COA Circular No. 92-382;

Strengthen internal control over collections, remittances and deposits to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the accountable officers (AOs) and consider the promulgation and implementation of a policy on the following:

i. On the turnover of daily collections, such as establishing a cut-off on the time of turnover which will give the Municipal Treasurer enough time to deposit the turned-over collections; and
ii. On imposing a penalty for holding of collections for several days in the hands of accountable officers.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly adhere to the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations relative to the granting and liquidation of CAs;
Require the concerned officials and employees, particularly the Municipal Treasurer, to settle or refund the unliquidated CAs of ₱17,851,972.03, and impose appropriate legal actions to enforce its collections or settlement;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to: (i) refrain from making CAs for various or general purpose and ensure that the same must be for specific purpose or particular type of expense; (ii) settle the enormous amount of unliquidated CAs of ₱14,350,938.27, and liquidation must be for the total amount of particular CA and any excess must be refunded and issued with corresponding receipt to avoid accumulation of outstanding balances;
Require the Municipal Accountant to strengthen its internal control in CAs such as (i) do not authorize, grant or facilitate additional CAs to Officers and employees, particularly the Municipal Treasurer,  if the previous CA balance is unsettled; (ii) enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding CAs, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement; (iii) do not approve the clearance from money accountability of retiring, resigning or transferring Officers and employees, if their respective CAs are not settled;
We also require the Municipal Accountant to submit the CAs liquidation vouchers and report of disbursements which are still unsubmitted to COA; and
Verify the collectability of unliquidated CAs of more than 10 years, otherwise, request the authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management to:
a.	Strictly comply with the provisions of R.A. No. 10121, and Item 5.1.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012, ensuring that the STF -MDRRM must be utilized for LDRRM activities;
b.	The Municipal Accountant and MDRRM Officer must be cautious in the preparation of MDRRM Utilization Report and other Reports relative to LDRRM, ensuring that the same are complete and accurate;
c.	Provide detailed justification as to the sudden disappearance of unspent LDRRM Fund in CY 2022 for the years 2018 to 2020 in the total amount of ₱992,315.82, and why the same was not reflected in the MDRRM Fund Utilization Report for the month of January 2023 and onwards;
d.	Provide justification as to the sudden appearance of unexpended STF balance for the years 2021 to 2022 in the MDRRMF Utilization Report for January 2023 amounting to ₱2,377.62, despite non-existent in the Financial Statements for CY 2022 as well as in MDRRMF Utilization Report in December 2022; and
e.	Submit the disbursement voucher for the construction of DOPCEN in the net amount of ₱752,810.30.

We recommended that Management:
Require the LSB to strictly comply with the provisions of DepEd, DBM and DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and Section 272 of RA No. 7160, such as:
Formulate a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;
Formulate and issue budget prioritization policies and tentative budget ceilings of the Municipality thru a Budget Call;
Prepare a SEF Budget;
Submit the quarterly and annual reports using the SEF Budget Accountability Form No. 1 (Annex B) on SEF utilization, as prepared by the Local Accountant, to the DepEd CO; and
Post the utilization report of the SEF Budget in the website of the LGU and/or in at least three (3) conspicuous public places.
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit to LSB actual SEF Income – quarterly, annual for the preceding and issuing year, and submit to COA the quarterly and annual SEF Utilization report for purposes of monitoring and audit, and ensure that CAs must be supported with complete documentation; and
Require the Municipal Treasurer to be cautious in the issuance of check bearing in mind the material effect on the availability of budget as well as on the fairness of FS presentation, and continuous errors in the issuance of check may constitute gross negligence of duty.

We recommended and Management agreed, with the Offices of the Mayor, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer as leads, to reinforce the application of the rules and regulations pertaining to the grant, liquidation and/or settlement of cash advances to exact accountability by:
a. requiring approval on the face of the cash advance voucher that said official/employee has no preceding unliquidated cash advance;
b. issuing demand letter/s for advances already due and demandable and halt salary releases if the official/employee still fails to liquidate the cash advance within the specified time frame;
c. designating a Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) for advances for special undertaking for proper control and monitoring of the grants and liquidations; and
d. drawing necessary journal entries to appropriately recognize settlement of outstanding cash advances.

With the areas of improvement noted, the following advancement measures are co- developed with management:
a. Capacitate and enhance the General Services Office (GSO) and the Inventory Committee in the over-all conduct of the required PPE count;
b. The Municipal Accounting Office shall capacitate and delegate the task on the establishment and maintenance and update of PPE Ledger Cards for reporting purposes; and the Supply Officer to set-up and maintain Property Cards for an efficient monitoring and reconciliations of the agency’s PPE with that of the accounting;
c. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data pertaining to PPEs as a basis for recording in the book and providing proper depreciation to all depreciable assets;
d. Institute mechanism controls over the safekeeping of all legal documents concerning LGU’s owned PPE; and
e. Revisit RA No. 656 and COA Circular No. 2018-002 for guidelines and procedures to follow in securing comprehensive and adequate insurance coverage for government properties.

With these deficiencies, we recommended the following:
a. Establish additional controls by opening and maintaining a separate bank account for 5% Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund for accountability and reporting purposes;
b. Institute additional internal control measures over the grant of cash advances for officers and employees by discontinuing the grant of additional advances to those with unliquidated ones;
c. Create Inventory Committees to timely and strategically plan the conduct of complete physical count of PPE and prepare/submit the corresponding RCPPE and IRRUP and reconciles the results of the count with the GSO and accounting records;
d. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data/information pertaining to the donated and disposed PPE as basis in the book recording;
e. Maintain the PPELCs and PCs to facilitate reconciliation and fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the books; and
f. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data/ documents pertaining to the unverified/unconfirmed loans payable and due to NGAs balances in the books of accounts before resorting to a request for an authority to write off dormant fund transfer provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

To improve performance under the 20% DF, we recommended the following measures:
a. Review and analyze the causes of the low and non-implementation of the 20% DF projects, programs and activities, and adopt effective strategies to address them, ensuring that the development objectives for which the fund has been created are completely carried out and implemented for the long-term benefits of the constituents;
b. Strictly adhere to the guidelines under the DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 in the utilization of the 20% development fund;
c. Require the Municipal Engineer to submit the Statement of Work Accomplished and other necessary documents pertaining to the implementation of the above-enumerated infrastructure projects; and
d. Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to conduct periodic monitoring of the PPAs funded by the 20% development fund to ensure optimal utilization of the fund.

Therefore, we reiterated our recommendation last year that management do the following:
a. Exert effort to demand immediately the liquidation of all outstanding cash advances from the concerned officials/employees who are still connected to the Municipality pursuant to COA Circulars 97-002 and 2012-004;
b. Impose sanctions prescribed in the said Circulars for non-compliance thereof, such as withholding the salaries and other emoluments of the officials/employees who continuously disregard, fail or decline to comply with the demand, including filing appropriate charges against them;
c. Send demand letters to officials and employees who are no longer connected with the Municipality but whose whereabouts are still known to liquidate their cash advances and consider taking legal actions/remedy against them; and
d. Gather all documents that will prove that liquidation of the named individuals was no longer possible such as those who are already deceased (e.g., death certificate) and whose last address was not known (e.g., retirement certification, clearances, etc.) and request for the write off of the receivable for fair presentation of the account in the Financial Statements taking into consideration the liability of those individuals who granted the clearances.

Require the LSB to formulate a three-year program for strategic allocation of the SEF for public schools’ needs;

Give preferential attention to the allocation and implementation of PPAs that could help support public schools in their operations and maintenance through the Annual SEF Budget;

Through the LSB, utilize the SEF Budget efficiently and effectively by prioritizing programs and activities that would help improve the operations of public schools for the benefit of the teachers, students and other stakeholders; and

Strictly observe the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 in the utilization of the SEF for its intended purpose.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Requesting Officers in the procurement of medicines to review the provisions of EO No. 49, s. 1993 and ensure the Agency’s compliance with the same, as such, a certification signed by the Requesting Officer that the drug products being requisitioned or procured conform with PNDF Volume I, otherwise, prepare a written request in accordance with such EO;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the required documentary requirements supporting all purchases especially for drugs and medicines are present. Be cautious in recording the financial transactions  and use the asset method in recording inventory instead of expensing them directly in the books;
Direct the GSO or concerned Supply or Property Personnel to ensure that the PO  is properly accomplished, particularly of date of delivery, which were mostly omitted or neglected; and
Direct the Property/Supply Officer and the Municipal Accountant to monitor the movement of stocks thru the use and maintenance of RIS and stock cards/stock ledger cards.

We recommended that Management:
Enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding cash advances, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen the internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances by complying with the provisions under Section Nos. 4 and 5 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation reports within the reglementary period;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who still have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and
Verify the collectability of unliquidated cash advances of more than 10 years, otherwise, request the authority to write-off dormant accounts guided by the conditions and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management:
Require the GSO/ Property Officer to ensure that, in all instances, any request for repair must be accompanied by Pre Inspection Report. Afterwards, the Waste Material Report and Post Inspection Report must be accomplished accordingly. Likewise, the GSO or Property Officer must also prepare and submit the complete technical description of the equipment and copy of document indicating the history of repair and submit the same to COA together with the Contract or Purchase Order within five days from perfection of Contract;
Require the Municipal Accountant to refrain from processing payment for repairs if the material documents required in COA Circular 2012-001 are not attached;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to refrain from requesting payment of transaction in the absence of complete documentation and without valid justification for its immediate payment, particularly the Official Receipt which is quite material, otherwise he would be committing grave abuse of discretion and malversation of government funds;
Submit to COA Office the lacking documents of the above mentioned payments for repair of equipment/ vehicle in the total amount of ₱1,187,089.92 as required in COA Circular 2012-001. Failure to do so may result to the issuance of Notice of Suspension of the above transactions; and
Require the GSO/Property Officer to submit the copies of complete technical description of the equipment and copy of document indicating the history of repair of each of all the equipment subjected to repair as mentioned above.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the LGU officials and employees to submit promptly their claims together with complete relevant supporting documents to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;
Hire additional competent staffs and personnel in the Accounting Office to accommodate the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality, and to hasten the process of submission of the necessary accounts to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate the process of preparing the disbursement vouchers, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must only be undertaken when they were properly approved and with complete documentation; and
Remind the concerned officials and employees of the administrative or criminal liability, under Section 39 (1) (3) of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code, as amended by Section 41 of Republic Act (RA) No. 10951, which may be imposed as a consequence of their inability or refusal to render accounts without justifiable cause.

