Compel the contractor to repair the existing defects and deficiencies of the project by removing and replacing the concrete portion of the project in compliance with the Order of PRDP Inspectorate Team;

Show cause why no liquidated damages were impose to the contractor for the delayed implementation of the project as required in Section 68 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act (RA) 9184;

For succeeding PRDP Projects, take appropriate action, legal or otherwise, to compel the contractor to complete the project in due time; and

Promptly organize the PRDP MPMIU before or at an earlier stage of the project implementation in order to effectively and efficiently manage the implementation of PRDP subproject so as to minimize or avoid delay in its implementation/ completion.

Take appropriate and immediate action to warrant full operation of the Charcoal Briquette Enterprise especially in the reorganization of personnel to manage the enterprise;

Ensure that the new Personnel Organization is competent to manage and operate the enterprise to ensure its operation and sustainability of income generating livelihood to its intended beneficiaries;

Conduct training programs to members/ personnel involve in Charcoal Briquette production, if needed, in order to improve its operation instead of purchasing various machineries and equipment which may not be currently used in operation; and

Furnish the COA Auditor with I-REAP Procurement Plan to verify the validity of procurement.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to revert the entry made to transfer the PPE account from the PRDP TF to the GF books;

Require the I-REAP focal person/s to submit the complete documents relevant to the project to the Office of the Auditor; and

Instruct the concerned officers to revisit and strictly follow the provisions of the PRDP Manual, specifically the I-REAP component, to ensure its compliance at all times.

Strictly observe the timeline for submission of Financial Reports and Financial Statements in accordance with the existing rules and regulations;

Submit the financial statements and other accounting reports that are already due for submission; and

Identify and resolve the causes of delay and non-submission of the mandatory financial statements and project reports with complete supporting documents/schedules within the prescribed period, otherwise, institute appropriate sanctions against the responsible officers for the continued non-compliance with existing regulations.

With these deficiencies, we recommended the following:
a. Address the causes/gaps in the non-preparation and non-submission of the required Monthly Bank Reconciliations Statements;
b. Revisit workload plan among the personnel in the Municipal Accounting Office by ensuring fair and balance workloads and elimination of work redundancies among them, to comply with preparation and submission of the required reports;
c. Address all the causes of non-liquidations by all accountable employees and officers. Request for write-off of the accounts proven impossible of collectability. Cause analysis and reconciliations of records and issuance of demand letters to concerned officials and employees with outstanding cash advances;
d. Establish additional controls by opening and maintaining a separate bank account for 5% Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund for accountability and reporting purposes;
e. Institute additional internal control measures over the grant of cash advances for officers and employees by discontinuing the grant of additional advances to those with unliquidated ones;
