g. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data/information pertaining to the donated and disposed PPE as basis in the book recording;
h. Maintain the PPELCs and PCs to facilitate reconciliation and fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the books;
i. Exhaust all efforts to locate relevant data/ documents pertaining to the unverified/unconfirmed loans payable and due to NGAs balances in the books of accounts before resorting to a request for an authority to write off dormant fund transfer provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
j. Take up appropriate Reclassifying/Adjusting Journal Entries (RAJE/PAJEs) to fairly present the affected account balances in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a.	Draft a demand letter, to be signed by the Mayor requiring the concerned officers and employees to submit immediately their liquidation reports duly supported with pertinent documents and refund the unexpended balance of cash advance to the Collecting Officer; 
b.	Stop granting additional cash advances to all officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that these would be fully settled; adhere to the provision of COA Circular No. 2012-001 on documentary requirements before granting cash advance; 
c.	Monitor regularly the liquidation of cash advances and to withhold any amount due to all AOs who refuses to liquidate their outstanding cash advances despite demand as provided for in the same circular.

We recommended and Management agreed that the GSO:
Complete the conduct of inventory taking of all PPE of the LGU;
Secure a copy of the PPE Ledger Cards from the Accounting Unit which can be used as a guide in the preparation of PPE inventory list by category and the Property Cards;
For the unserviceable properties, prepare a list of those items for disposal and all the necessary documents following Section 162 to 168 as prescribed under COA Circular No. 92-386 and COA Circular 89-296.
Identify who are accountable for the missing or unlocated properties by tracing the recipients from the Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment (ARE). The concerned accountable officer should request for relief from property accountability if the loss was not due to his/her negligence otherwise he/she should be held liable for the replacement cost of such property or equipment. 
Also, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant transfer the recording of all PPE under the Trust Fund to General Fund and provide the same with depreciation. Also, secure copies of turn-over and acceptance report by the recipients barangays/Liga for the 9 units single motor vehicle and prepare adjusting entry to drop the cost of the same from the books.

We recommended that Management undertake the following courses of actions:

Direct the concerned implementing office to determine the cause of delay in the completion of flatbed driers and if found out that it was due to the contractor’s fault impose penalties as provided in the contract or compute liquidated damages, if warranted. For the delayed completion of Village type corn post-harvest processing center please refer to recommendation under AOM No. 2018-007(2017);
Require the MA to secure copy of certificate of acceptance from the recipient beneficiaries for the transferred equipment for establishment of accountability and furnish the same to the Auditor;
Instruct the MA to devise an effective monitoring and evaluation tool that would provide Management and other interested users with information on the status and impact of the BUB projects in order to determine whether the objective of the BUB program was attained through the introduction of these projects in the community. The information can also be used for future decision making or reference for future project proposals;
Require the Engineering Department to look into the problem of water connection in the Kaong processing building and exert effort to assist the PO beneficiary in its financial issues so that they can start its operation as soon as possible. 
Fast track the procurement of the needed equipment for the operation of the E-Kawayan Processing plant.
Assist the camote farmers in looking for a better potential buyer of their harvest so that they will be able to sustain this livelihood program.
Lastly, enjoined implementing office to conduct a thorough study and research of the project to be proposed for funding under the BUB program in order to avoid delay in the implementation, completion and commencement of operation of the projects, thereby attainment of the objective for which these funds were created and ensuring that government funds and resources are protected from possible wastage.

