We recommend that Management undertake the following steps to account for all existing PPE items in the LGU:

•	Create an  Inventory Committee specifically for the accounting of all existing PPE items in the Municipality;
•	To facilitate the conduct of inventory require each office/unit to conduct their respective inventory-taking, tagging (inventory stickers) and recording of all PPE items present in their respective offices and the same shall be validated by the Inventory Committee and the General Services Office;
•	The GSO shall consolidate all validated inventory reports from the respective offices, which shall be the basis for preparation of Property Cards and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
•	The GSO shall furnish the Accounting Unit the copies of the RPCPPE for their reconciliation with the accounting records; and
•	The Accounting Unit shall determine any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and accounting records and prepare the necessary Property Ledger to record all unaccounted PPE items.
•	Fast track the processing of the titling of the municipal lot to ensure ownership of the property. 
•	The Municipal Accountant shall determine all properties which were already in the possession of the schools and other national agencies to effect the transfer of recording of the cost thereof to books of the latter, to present fairly the financial statements of the municipality.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
As a withholding agent of the Government, the management must compute, deduct and remit the exact amount of withholding tax pursuant to the January 1, 2009 table to conform with the Tax Reform Act of 1997 and to ensure that employees will not be burdened by paying high amounts of taxes that need to be paid in lump sum at year end and possible penalties for late payment of taxes on compensation;
Deduct and remit PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG contributions as required by the IRR of RA 7875 and RA 9679, respectively;
Follow the order of priority in deducting the mandatory and allowable deductions to the salaries of the employees; and
Preparation of payroll must be prepared by the Accounting Unit of the Municipality.

We recommended for the Municipal Accountant to take the following courses of action:

Validate and account for the details of the long outstanding unidentified Construction in Progress account totaling P11,412,851.64; 
Coordinate closely with other concerned department heads particularly with the Municipal Engineer as to the details of the CIP accounts; 
Maintain separate subsidiary ledgers or CIPLC (Construction in Progress Ledger Cards-Annex 12 NGAS Manual Volume II) on per project basis and; 

Ensure that in accounting for CIP, only on-going and uncompleted projects are reflected.

On comprehensive conduct of physical count:
Conduct a thorough physical count of PPE headed by the GSO and the Municipal Treasurer and identify the properties counted under each category for easy reconciliation with the records of the Municipal Accountant;
Retrieve all necessary documents in the transfer of completed projects under SEF or Trust Fund and transfer the same to the General Fund books. Subject the transferred property to depreciation
Update ARE every three years after issuance to ensure that property is still under the accountability of the accountable officer to whom property was issued;
Issue Inventory Custodian Slip on properties considered as small tangible items pursuant to COA Circular 2005-02 (Annex C) in coordination with COA Circular No. 97-005 (Annex D);
Maintain and update the PPELC as well as the different property ledgers;
Maintain and update property cards by the Property Custodian; and
Reconcile the PPELC, property cards and the physically counted properties
On properties not provided with depreciation
Exert all efforts to secure the documents of properties not provided with depreciation; and
Appraise all properties not provided with depreciation and make a sound decision on the amounts of impairments to present fairly the balances of the PPE and then provide depreciation;
On trust fund properties
Exert effort to locate documents related to the booked-up under Trust Fund;
Secure documents related to the PPEs recorded in the Trust Fund books, if none can be retrieved from the file of the Municipality, by communicating with the funding agency; and
Transfer all completed projects’ properties to General Fund and subject the same to depreciation.
Therefore, we recommended that budget for the stickers for the ensuing year will be provided to ensure that labels which are pre-numbered will be tagged in the body of the property with details as to property number, location of the property, description of the property, date of inventory, and signature of the personnel conducting the count.
Further, we recommended that an invitation must be sent to the resident COA auditor to witness the inventory taking.

Therefore, we recommended the following to ensure that Cash in Bank balance is fairly presented in the Financial Statements:
Exert effort to trace the documents for the unrecorded bank accounts and include the same in the Cash in Bank balance;
Refer to the granting agency if no liquidation report is necessary to close the grant;
If remaining amount will accrue to the benefit of the Municipality, revert balances of the account to the General Fund to close the existing accounts;
As regards the two dormant accounts, we recommend that analysis on the dormancy of the account must be made and proper action must be undertaken pursuant to EO No. 341.
Management admitted their lapses that could have caused the above audit findings. They, however, promised that steps will be taken to ensure that unrecorded bank accounts will be recorded in the books of the Municipality and dormant accounts will be kept updated.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
Update the cashbook based on the Report of Collections and Deposits submitted by Revenue Liquidating Officer on a daily basis;
Close the cashbooks at the end of each month by double-ruling below the last entries in the cashbook, showing further the running balances;
Certify all cashbooks at the end of each quarter;
Record the COH on a monthly basis collections made for SEF and Trust Funds;
At least once per quarter, pursuant to the above ruling, the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of their books and to reflect all reconciling items in both books affected to support the assertion of the Municipality on the balances of the Cash in Bank, Cash Local Treasury and Payroll accounts as presented in the Financial Statement.
Moreover, management is requested to furnish the Commission a copy of the reconciliation made for transparency and aid in audit.
The management was amenable on the audit findings and agreed to undertake the audit recommendations.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
Trace the cause of the discrepancy and make the necessary adjustments in the books of either the Treasurer’s or the Accountant’s, whichever had errors in recording;
Reconcile the books/records of the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant on a regular basis;
All discrepancies noted must be acted immediately.
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer promised to reconcile their records and make the necessary adjustments pursuant to the audit recommendations.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
Submit Annual Budget to Sangguniang Bayan on time if not earlier and  make representation for the prompt enactment of the Annual Budget and the timely approval of possible revised plans on Infrastructure PPAs;
Revisit and analyze amounts appropriated for LGU equity for foreign and national assisted projects that an amount provided will be realistic that ensures accomplishments of projects before the year it pertained to ends;
Require focal persons to fast track the liquidation of those funded projects from foreign and national agencies to guarantee release of future requested projects thus appropriated LGU counterparts out of the20% DF will be utilized.
The management was amenable to the audit findings and promised that steps will be taken to fast tract the implementation of projects that were already approved in previous years. The Municipal Engineer targeted that by June 2017, all CY 2016 projects will already be started and hopefully finished by that time.

We recommend that Management undertake the following steps to account for all existing PPE items in the LGU:
Create an  Inventory Committee specifically for the accounting of all existing PPE items in the Municipality;
To facilitate the conduct of inventory require each office/unit to conduct their respective inventory-taking, tagging (inventory stickers) and recording of all PPE items present in their respective offices and the same shall be validated by the Inventory Committee and the General Services Office;
The GSO shall consolidate all validated inventory reports from the respective offices, which shall be the basis for preparation of Property Cards and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
The GSO shall furnish the Accounting Unit the copies of the RPCPPE for their reconciliation with the accounting records; and
The Accounting Unit shall determine any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and accounting records and prepare the necessary Property Ledger to record all unaccounted PPE items.
Fast track the processing of the titling of the municipal lot to ensure ownership of the property.
The Municipal Accountant shall determine all properties which were already in the possession of the schools and other national agencies to effect the transfer of recording of the cost thereof to books of the latter, to present fairly the financial statements of the municipality.

Therefore, we recommended to the Management:
Change the scheme of the remittance of the collection of collectors to the Liquidating Officer in accordance to Section 29 of NGAS Volume 1, that is, to remit to the Liquidating Officer all collections made during the day at the close of each business day for those situated near the Municipality’s Office and at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach P5,000.00 for those Collectors whose official station will take more than one day to travel;
No additional stub will be issued to the collector unless the former/remaining stubs on collector’s hand were already liquidated by him/her to the liquidating officer;
Prepare a pre-formatted Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) to be filled-up manually by the collectors duly signed by them to ensure prompt remittance of collections.

Therefore, in view of the above deficiencies/gaps noted in the procurement activities of the Municipality, we recommended the following:

Strict adherence to the provisions of RA 9184 and the Procurement Manual of the Local Government Unit in future procurement undertakings, such as but not limited to the following:
Provide the necessary/information information in the posted Philgeps purchases;
Utilize the use of the Philippines Bidding Documents;
No references to brand names by being specific on the specifications present only to a particular product instead make a general specification;
Follow procedures before resorting to negotiated procurements;
Do not employ “kaliwaan system”, and

Equip concerned officials especially the BAC with proper knowledge in carrying out functions, duties and responsibilities by attending series of seminars and trainings on RA 9184.

Direct Management to: a) instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct an annual actual physical count of all PPE items including the preparation and submission of the consolidated inventory report/ RPCPPE; and b) require the accounting section to maintain PPELC and property unit for property cards indicating the details, quantities, exact date of acquisition, and status/condition of all PPE items and property cards to be kept by the designated property officer.
Further, the following procedures shall be observed by the General Service Officer, to wit:
Secure complete list of property, plant and equipment listed in the PPE Ledger Cards;
Conduct inventory tagging for the PPE; 
Secure copies of Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment issued to each     individual who uses the equipment;
Compare the property and equipment against record appearing in the ARE to ensure correctness;
Take note of those ARE issued without physical inventory presented;
Take note of those property and equipment found to be without ARE issued;
List those that are found to be damaged or those property and equipment already obsolete or unserviceable and
Institute action for those property and equipment lost, damaged or not found.
